://web.archive.org/web/20160405104332/http://zicklin.baruch.cuny.edu/faculty/profiles/joyce.html# | archive-date=2016-04-05 | dead-url=yes | df= }}</ref> ==Research== Joyce conducts research in the fields of [[health economics]] and [[health policy]].<ref name=cuny/> For example, he has published multiple studies on the effects of [[abortion law]]s. These include a 2011 perspective piece comparing the effectiveness of [[supply-side]] and demand-side laws in reducing rates of abortions performed after 16 weeks which found that the former were much more effective than the latter.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2014/10/the-safer-more-affordable-abortion-only-available-in-two-states/381321/ | title=The Safer, More Affordable Abortion Only Available in Two States | work=The Atlantic | date=10 October 2014 | accessdate=20 April 2016 | author=Semuels, Alana}}</ref> He has also published research showing that [[Minors and abortion|parental involvement laws]] were not associated with significant changes in the overall abortion rate, but that they had small effects on some subgroups of minors.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/06/national/06abortion.html?pagewanted=print&_r=0 | title=Scant Drop Seen in Abortion Rate if Parents Are Told | work=New York Times | date=6 March 2006 | accessdate=20 April 2016 | author=Lehren, Andres}}</ref> In a 2006 study, he and his colleagues found that Texas' parental notification law was associated with a significant decline in the abortion rate among Texas teenagers.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/03/08/AR2006030802077.html | title=Drop in Abortions, Notification Law Linked | work=Washington Post | date=8 March 2006 | accessdate=20 April 2016 | author=Associated Press}}</ref>
